"{\"lesson_json\":\"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"calculate-quilt-squares\\\",\\\"title\\\":\\\"Calculate Quilt Squares\\\",\\\"description\\\":\\\"Calculate the number of squares for a quilt\\\",\\\"template\\\":\\\"quilt_width = 8 \\\\nquilt_length = 12 \\\\n\\\\n# Calculate total squares needed\\\\nprint(quilt_width * quilt_length)\\\\n\\\\n# Update quilt dimensions\\\\nquilt_length = 8\\\\n\\\\n# Calculate total squares needed after update\\\\nprint(quilt_width * quilt_length)\\\\n\\\",\\\"solution\\\":\\\"quilt_width = 8\\\\nquilt_length = 12\\\\nprint(quilt_width * quilt_length)\\\\nquilt_length = 8\\\\nprint(quilt_width * quilt_length)\\\\n\\\",\\\"entrypoint\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"inputs\\\":{},\\\"time\\\":6,\\\"mode\\\":\\\"line\\\"}\",\"lesson_markdown\":\"# Calculate Quilt Squares\\n\\nIn this lesson, you will learn how to use variables to calculate the number of squares needed for a quilt. Variables can hold numeric values, which can be manipulated just like regular numbers. This allows you to perform calculations easily.\\n\\nLet's start by creating two variables: `quilt_width` and `quilt_length`. For your first quilt, you want it to be 8 squares wide and 12 squares long. Here\u2019s how you can do that:\\n\\n```python\\nquilt_width = 8  # Width of the quilt in squares\\nquilt_length = 12  # Length of the quilt in squares\\n\\n# Calculate total squares needed\\nprint(quilt_width * quilt_length)  # This will give you the total number of squares needed for the quilt\\n```\\n\\nWhen you run this code, it will print the total number of squares needed for your quilt.\\n\\nNow, let\u2019s suppose you need to change your quilt's dimensions. If you decide to make the quilt only 8 squares long instead of 12, you can update the `quilt_length` variable and perform the calculation again:\\n\\n```python\\n# Update quilt dimensions\\nquilt_length = 8  # New length of the quilt in squares\\n\\n# Calculate total squares needed after update\\nprint(quilt_width * quilt_length)  # This will give you the new total number of squares needed\\n```\\n\\nThis shows you how to update the variable and recalculate the total squares needed. Remember, updating the variable does not affect the original value until you assign it a new value!\\n\",\"lesson_typescript\":\"import { useEffect } from \\\"react\\\";\\n\\nimport { useLessonStore } from \\\"@/store/lessonStore\\\";\\nimport { useTraceFinished } from \\\"@/utils/taskChecks\\\";\\n\\nimport content from \\\"./calculate-quilt-squares.md?raw\\\";\\n\\nexport function useCalculateQuiltSquares(lessonId: string) {\\n  const { startLesson, completeTask, currentTask } = useLessonStore();\\n  const traceFinished = useTraceFinished();\\n\\n  useEffect(() => {\\n    if (lessonId !== \\\"calculate-quilt-squares\\\") return;\\n    // Start the lesson\\n    startLesson(lessonId, content, [\\n      {\\n        id: \\\"calculate-squares\\\",\\n        title: \\\"Calculate total squares\\\",\\n        description: \\\"Calculate the total number of squares needed for the quilt\\\",\\n      },\\n      {\\n        id: \\\"update-squares\\\",\\n        title: \\\"Update quilt dimensions\\\",\\n        description: \\\"Update the quilt length and recalculate total squares\\\",\\n      },\\n    ]);\\n  }, [lessonId, startLesson]);\\n\\n  useEffect(() => {\\n    if (currentTask?.id === \\\"calculate-squares\\\") {\\n      if (traceFinished) {\\n        completeTask();\\n      }\\n    }\\n    if (currentTask?.id === \\\"update-squares\\\") {\\n      if (traceFinished) {\\n        completeTask();\\n      }\\n    }\\n  }, [currentTask, completeTask, traceFinished]);\\n}\"}"